// =============================================================================
// security/zk/mod.vr — Zero-knowledge proof systems
// =============================================================================
// Layer: 3 (cryptography)
// =============================================================================
//

// Two zero-knowledge proof systems, complementary in their guarantees:
//
//   * **Halo2 + KZG10** — Plonk-style proofs over BLS12-381. Tiny
//     proofs (~1-2 KB), fast verifier, recursion-friendly via the Halo
//     accumulator design. **Pre-quantum** (security rests on AGM +
//     DLog over BLS12-381). Best for short-life proofs and rollup
//     aggregators.
//   * **STARK + FRI** — Reed-Solomon IOP with FRI low-degree test.
//     Larger proofs (~50-200 KB), comparable verifier speed, recursion
//     at logarithmic cost. **Post-quantum secure** under collision-
//     resistance of the underlying hash (BLAKE3). Best for long-lived
//     attestations and PQ-roadmap deployments.
//
// Both systems share the *circuit-DSL* design pattern: the user
// constructs an immutable description of the relation to prove
// (`Circuit` for Halo2, `Air` for STARK), then invokes the prover
// with witness inputs. Verifier-side artifacts (`VerifyingKey` /
// `AirVk`) are content-addressed.
//
// The two share generic helpers as far as practical (range-proofs,
// set-membership, hash-preimage). Where the underlying constraint
// language differs (custom gates vs. transition polynomials) the
// helpers diverge.
//
// =============================================================================

@arch_module(
    foundation: Foundation.ZfcTwoInacc,
    stratum: MsfsStratum.LFnd,
    lifecycle: Lifecycle.Conditional([
        "BLS12-381 + BLAKE3 stdlib lands (done)",
        "ZK prover backends bound at runtime layer",
    ]),
)
module core.security.zk;

public module halo2;
public module stark;
